            "answer_text": "In absolute terms, it's about the charge of [math]6.241 \\times 10^{18}[/math] electrons, but unfortunately that probably doesn't give you much of an intuitive feel for it! We can try talking about how big a coulomb is relative to everyday things, and maybe that will bring it into focus? Unfortunately, even that approach can end up confounding our instincts.  For instance, according to Wikipedia, about 5000 C are released during the life of a typical AA battery, but only 15 C are transmitted by a typical lightening bolt!  (Coulomb in everyday terms) Sooooooooooo, where does that leave us?  What can we say, using familiar terms, about how big 1 coulomb is? Not much.  :-( The fact is that charge isn't a quantity that we have much direct interaction with.  We mostly experience charge indirectly, through it's effect on other things.  For instance, in the AA battery vs. lightening bolt example, the more important difference is not the amount of charge, but the amount of energy.  Of course, there's way more energy released by a lightning bolt than in the discharge of a AA battery, it's just that the work is being done by fewer electrons.  (About 9000 joules in a battery, about 5 billion joules in a lightening bolt.) So the lesson here, I think, is that the coulomb is a great unit for technical contexts, but a poor unit for conveying intuition. That's a bit of a wishy-washy answer, but I hope it provided some food for thought! ",
