            "answer_text": "Did you mean, how wide is one coulomb, physically? We can answer that by looking at copper, looking at wires. Answer: a coulomb is roughly half a millimeter wide. (This only applies to the movable electrons found inside wires.) In copper metal, each atom donates one (conduction-band) outer electron to the common \u201csea of charge.\u201d The rest of copper atoms\u2019 electrons remain bound to each atom, all balanced by the opposite positive charge in the nucleus. We can view copper metal as containing an \u201celectron fluid,\u201d where the density of electrons is the same as the density of atoms in the metal: one free electron per atom. (So, we\u2019re only looking at the mobile coulombs of the copper; the coulombs which can participate in currents, rather than counting up the total coulombs present.) The atoms/cc density for copper is 8.5*10^22. That becomes our value for electrons/cc density. And, the charge of one electron is 1.6*10^-19 coulombs. Multiply together, and that gives us a charge density for copper: 13600 coulombs per cubic centimeter. Therefore one coulomb forms a cube about 0.4mm on a side: 1/(13600^1/3) = 0.42mm Aha! One coulomb is about the size of a small grain of salt! If we had some wire with a cross-section area of .42mm, then during a one-ampere current, the electrons would be moving along like little .42mm cubes, one little cube per second, a drift speed of .42mm/sec, or one inch per minute. (See, electric current in metals is quite slow.) Well, all this only applies to copper metal. In other metals it will be somewhat different, and in salt water or damp earth (or electron-beams in vacuum tubes) it will be very different: much wider coulombs, much faster currents. Heh, next ask yourself: if voltage is like pressure, then 1.0 volts is how many PSI? ",
