            },
            "answer_text": "To explore this question, let us look at it by means of force over a distance. Force between two charges separated with a distance \u201cr\u201dcan be calculated by: F=q1*q2/(4*pi*epsilon_0*r^2). Now, assume 1C of positive charge is placed 1 m away from another 1C of positive charge. These two set of charges would apply a force outward to each other. Now, if we want to keep them in place and we connect them with a steel rod of 1 m diameter (and the length of 1m), the force would be so large that is would tear apart this steel rod. The force would be a tremendous ~10^10 N! To keep them in place we need a thicker steel rod. (Ultimate tensile strength of steel ~1000 Mpa which means we need a rod of diameter of nearly 3.7 m to hold those two set of 1C charge, 1 m away from each other). From another view a coulomb of charge is not a big deal. Recall that a coulomb is the amount of electrons transferred in one second by a current of one ampere. This amount of charge can be transferred by a AA battery and a resistor. ",
