            "answer_text": "That's a very intyeresting question, the lame and uninteresting answer to this seemingly innocent question would be, 1 netwon of force will be acting on this much charge which is present in an electric field of 1 N/C(newton/coloumb). But a more interesting answer would be, the charge of 1 electron is 1.6x10^(-19) coloumb. Thus we would need 10^(19) electrons to give 1.6 coloumbs of charge, now imagine 10^19 electrons. Although it seems like a big number, the number of atoms in a mole is about 6x(10^23) so in one mole of hydrogen gas we have 6x10^23 electrons, that is already about 40000 times more than required to make one 1.6 coloumb of charge. ",
